📝 Chapter 7: Diet and Growth - 40 MCQs
7.1 Nutrients
1. Which type of nutrient is broken down by the body into glucose to provide the main fuel for cellular respiration?
 A) Proteins B) Carbohydrates C) Vitamins D) Minerals
2. A student wants to build strong muscles and repair body tissues after a heavy workout. Which nutrient is most important for this?
 A) Fats B) Carbohydrates C) Protein D) Water
3. Fats and oils are very similar, but how do they generally differ at normal room temperature?
 A) Fats are liquid, oils are solid. B) Fats are solid, oils are liquid. C) Fats contain energy, oils do not. D) Fats are found in plants, oils are found in animals.
4. Which vitamin is particularly important for helping us see in the dark, and is found in green vegetables and carrots?
 A) Vitamin A B) Vitamin C C) Vitamin D D) Iron
5. Historically, sailors on long sea voyages without fresh fruit or vegetables suffered from scurvy, which caused swollen and bleeding gums
. Scurvy is caused by a lack of:
 A) Calcium B) Vitamin A C) Vitamin C D) Protein
6. 🧠 Thinking Skill: A doctor advises a patient who feels constantly exhausted and tired to eat more red meat and dark green vegetables
. What condition is the doctor most likely trying to treat?
 A) Rickets B) Scurvy C) Constipation D) Anaemia
7. How does the human body primarily obtain Vitamin D for strong bones and teeth?
 A) By eating large amounts of citrus fruits. B) It is made in the skin when sunlight falls onto it. C) By drinking plenty of water. D) By breaking down carbohydrates in the liver.
8. What is the main biological function of the mineral calcium?
 A) To make haemoglobin for red blood cells. B) To act as a solvent for chemical reactions. C) To make bones and teeth strong. D) To prevent constipation.
9. Why is water considered an essential part of the diet?
 A) It provides a long-term store of energy. B) It allows chemicals to dissolve and react in cells, and transports substances in the blood. C) It builds strong bones and cell membranes. D) It is broken down into glucose.
10. Fibre is mostly made of cellulose and is not actually digested by the body
. Why is it still essential to eat plenty of fibre?
 A) It provides a rapid energy spike. B) It helps to prevent constipation by keeping the digestive system healthy. C) It cures anaemia. D) It helps white blood cells fight pathogens.
11. A student tests a mystery food sample using iodine solution
. The solution turns from orange-brown to a very dark blue-black
. What does this prove?
 A) The food contains protein. B) The food contains Vitamin C. C) The food contains starch. D) The food contains fat.
12. 🧠 Thinking Skill: Why does a deficiency in iron directly lead to a lack of energy?
 A) Iron is the main fuel burned during respiration. B) Without iron, the body cannot absorb calcium. C) Lack of iron means less haemoglobin is made, so less oxygen is transported to cells for respiration. D) Iron is needed to digest carbohydrates.
7.2 A Balanced Diet
13. What defines a "balanced diet"?
 A) Eating only fruits and vegetables every day. B) Eating exactly the same mass of food at every meal. C) A diet that provides all the different kinds of nutrients, and the right amount of energy. D) A diet that eliminates all fats and carbohydrates.
14. Which of the following individuals would generally require the highest daily energy intake?
 A) An 8-year-old girl. B) A 50-year-old man with a desk job. C) A 15-year-old active teenage boy. D) A 3-month-old baby.
15. 🧠 Thinking Skill: A woman consumes 8 megajoules (MJ) of energy daily but uses 10 MJ of energy due to her highly active job
. What biological process will her body initiate to make up the difference?
 A) It will break down stored body fat to provide the missing energy. B) It will stop cellular respiration. C) It will convert proteins directly into fibre. D) It will store the 8 MJ as extra fat.
16. A pregnant woman needs an increased amount of calcium and protein in her diet
. What is the primary reason for this?
 A) To increase her own muscle mass. B) To build new cells and bones for her growing baby. C) To improve her night vision. D) To prevent scurvy.
17. 🧠 Thinking Skill: A student eats a meal of white rice, fried chicken, and a sugary soda. Which dietary component, essential for digestive health, is almost entirely missing from this meal?
 A) Protein B) Carbohydrates C) Dietary fibre D) Fats
18. Consuming too much animal fat in your diet increases the risk of developing which condition?
 A) Anaemia B) Rickets C) Heart disease D) Scurvy
19. Consuming excessive amounts of sugar not only causes tooth decay but also increases the risk of which illness?
 A) Diabetes B) Constipation C) Low blood pressure D) Malaria
20. In a healthy food triangle, which group of foods should make up the largest proportion of your diet?
 A) Sweets and fried foods. B) Meat, fish, and eggs. C) Dairy products like cheese and butter. D) Fresh fruit, vegetables, and whole grains.
21. 🧠 Thinking Skill: Why is it considered healthier to eat whole-grain bread or brown rice rather than white bread or white rice?
 A) Whole grains contain absolutely no carbohydrates. B) Whole grains provide more dietary fibre and vitamins. C) White rice contains too much vitamin D. D) White bread is a major source of iron.
22. If a person constantly eats more carbohydrates and fats than their body uses, what happens to the extra nutrients?
 A) They are immediately excreted as fibre. B) They are turned into extra haemoglobin. C) They are turned into fat and stored in the body, leading to weight gain. D) They are converted into calcium for bones.
7.3 Growth, Development, and Health
23. How does a single cell eventually become a fully grown baby?
 A) The single cell stretches indefinitely. B) The cell divides into two, and those cells grow and divide again repeatedly. C) The cell absorbs other cells from the mother's body. D) The cell solidifies into a bone.
24. 🧠 Thinking Skill: While "growth" simply means getting bigger, what does biological "development" involve?
 A) Only an increase in body fat. B) The formation of different tissues, organs, and the gaining of new skills (like walking or talking). C) The shedding of the exoskeleton. D) The process of losing baby teeth.
25. Which of the following is a physical benefit of taking regular exercise?
 A) It stores extra energy as fat. B) It makes the heart and muscles work hard, so they become strong. C) It slows down the digestive system. D) It decreases the body's need for oxygen.
26. Cigarette smoke contains several dangerous substances
. Which substance is the addictive stimulant that makes it difficult for smokers to quit?
 A) Tar B) Carbon monoxide C) Nicotine D) Particulates
27. Which harmful component of cigarette smoke coats the lungs, damages the sweeping hairs (cilia), and causes lung cancer?
 A) Nicotine B) Tar C) Carbon monoxide D) Calcium
28. 🧠 Thinking Skill: Carbon monoxide is a poisonous gas found in cigarette smoke
. It binds to haemoglobin much stronger than oxygen does. How does this specifically harm the smoker's body?
 A) It dissolves the stomach lining. B) It prevents red blood cells from carrying enough oxygen to cells for respiration. C) It causes the bones to become soft and bend. D) It makes the blood completely transparent.
29. Based on health data, how does smoking during pregnancy heavily impact the unborn baby?
 A) It increases the baby's birthweight. B) It significantly increases the chance of having a baby with a low birthweight. C) It causes the baby to grow extra muscles. D) It has absolutely no effect on the baby.
30. 🧠 Thinking Skill: If an 8-year-old child's diet severely lacks protein and energy, what is the most likely long-term outcome?
 A) They will develop superior night vision. B) They will grow much taller than their peers. C) Their cells will lack the materials and energy to divide, stunting their overall growth. D) Their skeleton will turn into an exoskeleton.
7.4 Moving the Body
31. What is the main function of the bones known as the cranium (skull) and the sternum (ribcage)?
 A) To pump blood around the body. B) To protect delicate internal organs like the brain, heart, and lungs. C) To digest carbohydrates. D) To absorb sunlight for Vitamin D production.
32. Some animals, like insects, have a hard skeleton on the outside of their bodies
. What is this called?
 A) Endoskeleton B) Exoskeleton C) Vertebral column D) Cartilage
33. The elbow and the knee allow movement back and forth in only one single direction
. What type of joints are these?
 A) Ball-and-socket joints B) Hinge joints C) Fixed joints D) Fused joints
34. What type of joint is found at the shoulder and the hip, allowing the arm or leg to move in a complete circle?
 A) Hinge joint B) Pivot joint C) Ball-and-socket joint D) Exoskeleton joint
35. Muscles are specialized cells that create movement. How do they do this?
 A) By expanding and pushing bones away. B) By contracting (making themselves shorter) to produce a pulling force. C) By bending around the joints. D) By vibrating rapidly.
36. Tough cords of connective tissue attach muscles directly to bones
. What are these cords called?
 A) Veins B) Cartilage C) Ligaments D) Tendons
37. 🧠 Thinking Skill: A fundamental rule of biomechanics is that muscles can only pull; they can never push
. Because of this, how must muscles be arranged to bend and then straighten a joint?
 A) As a single giant muscle that pulls in both directions. B) In antagonistic pairs, where one pulls to bend the joint and the other pulls to straighten it. C) In groups of four that vibrate the bone. D) In a parallel chain that expands the joint.
38. When you want to bend your arm at the elbow, what must the biceps and triceps muscles do?
 A) Both muscles must contract at the exact same time. B) The triceps contracts and the biceps relaxes. C) The biceps contracts (pulls) and the triceps relaxes. D) Both muscles relax completely.
39. 🧠 Thinking Skill: If a severe injury completely severed the tendon connecting a person's triceps muscle to their ulna bone, what specific movement would they be unable to perform?
 A) Bending their arm at the elbow. B) Straightening their arm at the elbow. C) Moving their fingers. D) Rotating their shoulder.
40. 🧠 Thinking Skill: Which sequence accurately describes the flow of energy required for a person to lift a heavy object?
 A) Tendon stretches → bone vibrates → muscle relaxes. B) Light energy → thermal energy → muscle pushes bone. C) Glucose + Oxygen → aerobic respiration in muscle cells → muscle contracts → tendon pulls bone. D) Muscle absorbs water → expands in size → joint straightens.
✅ Answer Key & Explanations for the Teacher
1. B (Carbohydrates are the main source of glucose for aerobic respiration)
. 2. C (Protein is vital for making new cells and repairing damaged tissues)
. 3. B (Fats are solid at room temperature, whereas oils are liquid)
. 4. A (Vitamin A is essential for good vision, especially in dark environments)
. 5. C (Vitamin C keeps skin/gums strong; scurvy is the deficiency disease)
. 6. D (Tiredness is a symptom of anaemia, which is caused by a lack of iron. Red meat and spinach are rich in iron)
. 7. B (While some food has it, most Vitamin D is synthesized by the skin in sunlight)
. 8. C (Calcium is the structural mineral in bones and teeth)
. 9. B (Water is a solvent for cellular reactions and the main component of blood plasma for transport)
. 10. B (Fibre adds bulk to waste, preventing constipation and maintaining gut health)
. 11. C (Iodine solution turning blue-black is the standard laboratory test for starch)
. 12. C (Iron is required to make haemoglobin. Less haemoglobin = less oxygen = less aerobic respiration to release energy)
. 13. C (A balanced diet requires all nutrients in the correct proportions, plus adequate energy)
. 14. C (Active teenagers need immense energy for both rapid growth and high physical activity)
. 15. A (If energy expenditure exceeds energy intake, the body burns stored fat to survive)
. 16. B (Protein and calcium are required to construct the new tissues and bones of the developing embryo/baby)
. 17. C (This meal is heavy in carbs and fats but completely lacks plant cell walls/roughage, meaning it lacks dietary fibre)
. 18. C (Excess animal fats are heavily linked to heart disease)
. 19. A (Excess sugar is a major risk factor for developing diabetes)
. 20. D (The base/largest part of the food triangle consists of grains, fruits, and vegetables for fibre and vitamins)
. 21. B (Whole grains retain their fibrous outer layers, making them excellent sources of fibre and vitamins)
. 22. C (Unused carbohydrates and fats are converted into body fat for long-term storage)
. 23. B (Growth occurs via cellular division and expansion)
. 24. B (Development encompasses the maturation of tissues, organ formation, and the acquisition of complex skills)
. 25. B (Exercise strengthens the cardiovascular and muscular systems)
. 26. C (Nicotine is the addictive drug in tobacco)
. 27. B (Tar is the sticky substance that paralyses cilia and contains carcinogens)
. 28. B (Carbon monoxide deprives the body of oxygen by permanently binding to red blood cells)
. 29. B (Smoking restricts oxygen/nutrients to the baby, severely stunting its growth and causing low birthweight)
. 30. C (Without protein to build cells and energy to fuel division, physical growth halts)
. 31. B (The skull protects the brain; the ribcage protects the heart and lungs)
. 32. B (An exoskeleton is a rigid external covering)
. 33. B (Hinge joints operate exactly like a door hinge, restricting motion to a single plane)
. 34. C (Ball-and-socket joints offer the widest range of motion, allowing circular movement)
. 35. B (Muscle tissue generates force exclusively by contracting/shortening)
. 36. D (Tendons are the tough, inelastic cords linking muscles to bones)
. 37. B (Because they cannot push, muscles must operate in opposing "antagonistic" pairs to reverse a movement)
. 38. C (To bend the arm, the flexor (biceps) contracts to pull the bone up, while the extensor (triceps) relaxes to allow the movement)
. 39. B (The triceps is responsible for pulling the ulna downwards to straighten the arm. If severed, this specific pulling force cannot be applied)
. 40. C (Chemical energy from glucose is unlocked via respiration to power muscle contraction, which pulls the tendon and moves the bone)
